{"copyright": {"licenseType": "NO", "determinationType": "OTHER", "thirdPartyContentCondition": "NOT_SET"}, "subjectCategories": ["Meteorology and Climatology"], "exportControl": {"isExportControl": "NO", "ear": "NO", "itar": "NO"}, "created": "2013-08-25T07:47:00.0000000+00:00", "distributionDate": "2019-07-11T00:00:00.0000000+00:00", "center": {"code": "SSC", "name": "Stennis Space Center", "id": "33a97101969844cb970ed05fda173514"}, "onlyAbstract": false, "sensitiveInformation": 2, "fundingNumbers": [{"number": "NNS06AA58G", "type": "CONTRACT_GRANT"}, {"number": "NNG04GI84G", "type": "CONTRACT_GRANT"}, {"number": "DAAD19-02-2-0005", "type": "CONTRACT_GRANT"}, {"number": "NNG04GH51G", "type": "CONTRACT_GRANT"}, {"number": "NNG04GL61G", "type": "CONTRACT_GRANT"}, {"number": "NSF ATM-0233780", "type": "CONTRACT_GRANT"}, {"number": "NNG04GB87G", "type": "CONTRACT_GRANT"}], "abstract": "Future meteorological satellites are expected to provide much needed fine-scale information that can improve the accuracy of weather and climate models. As one application of this improved capability, we introduce the concept of a generalized parameterization framework using satellite datasets that will increase the accuracy and the computational efficiency of weather and climate modeling. In an atmospheric model, several different parameterizations usually are used to reproduce the various physical processes. However, it is generally unrealistic to separate the processes in this artificial way since the observations and physics make no such artificial separation. Thus, we propose a new unified parameterization framework to remove the unrealistic separation between parameterizations.", "title": "Satellite-Based Model Parameterization of Diabatic Heating", "stiType": "REPRINT", "distribution": "PUBLIC", "submittedDate": "2013-08-25T07:47:00.0000000+00:00", "isLessonsLearned": false, "authorAffiliations": [{"sequence": 0, "submissionId": 20110014248, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Pielke, R